<span id="freeTextContainer960117624234499675"><a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/33917.The_Namesake' title='The Namesake by Jhumpa Lahiri' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Namesake</a> starts by introducing a Bengali couple, Ashoke and Ashima. Their marriage had been arranged by their parents, still customary in Bengali society in the 1960s. They are living in Cambridge, Massachusetts. Ashoke is pursuing a career in engineering. His wife, feeling isolated and alone, misses terribly friends and family in Calcutta, which she still considers “home”. In 1968, their first child is born. The story is primarily about him--we follow him through to his early thirties. <br/><br/>A ce</span>
  <span id="freeText960117624234499675" style="display:none"><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/33917.The_Namesake" title="The Namesake by Jhumpa Lahiri" rel="nofollow noopener">The Namesake</a> starts by introducing a Bengali couple, Ashoke and Ashima. Their marriage had been arranged by their parents, still customary in Bengali society in the 1960s. They are living in Cambridge, Massachusetts. Ashoke is pursuing a career in engineering. His wife, feeling isolated and alone, misses terribly friends and family in Calcutta, which she still considers “home”. In 1968, their first child is born. The story is primarily about him--we follow him through to his early thirties. <br /><br />A central theme is “being an immigrant”. The importance of name is another theme. Ultimately, the book is about growing up, finding one’s own identity--a process that involves forging a life on one’s own terms. That life must also assimilate into it family ties and one’s heritage. <br /><br />Let’s consider the first theme--being an immigrant. In my youth I was an immigrant. Undeniably, this affects how I view the book. I see immigration as a challenge, a fantastic opportunity. Rather than bemoaning what you no longer have, see the opportunities that lie before you. There is so much new and exciting to see and to learn. Here is a chance to invent and create something new for yourself. Personally, I see the positive in the possibilities that lie before one.<br /><br />There are as many ways of seeing immigration as there are immigrants. It is interesting to note that Ashoke and Ashima view the immigrant experience differently. With time the new surrounding will inevitably alter one’s routines and perspectives. Ashima, for the sake of her two children, began to celebrate Christmas. I thought it wrong of her to seek out other Bengalis in America; one can choose to live in an area where one is forced to make new friends.<br /><br />Having immigrant parents leaves a stamp on the children’s lives too. They are squeezed between two cultures, the old and the new. Which will they choose? Do they fit comfortably in either? Does the experience make them stronger? <br /><br />The first portion of the novel, set in the 1960s and 1970s, felt for me like a trip down memory lane. My kids were raised in the 70s. This part I enjoyed; the author captured this time period well. The TV shows, the toys, the games kids played, the popular bands, the very way one viewed life then is drawn well. Lahiri has the details right. <br /><br />We watch as Ashoke’s and Ashima’s two children grow from kids, to teenagers to adults. The story follows more intensively the son and in particular his search to find a life partner. Will that woman be a true-blooded American type, or will he choose a woman of Bengali heritage? He tries both. We observe his relationships. Lining them up one against the other is amusing; comparing the different lifestyles makes one smile. You consider the good and the bad of both.<br /><br />In covering such a long time span and alternative lifestyles, the story becomes too long. My interest lagged. The tribulations typical of coming of age stories are drawn. Little is new. Furthermore, the telling focuses only on affluent and successful immigrants. The son goes to Yale and Colombia University and becomes a <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[successful architect <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>.<br /><br />A theme covered that is not typical of coming of age tales is the importance of one’s name. How important is one’s name? Why is it so common to revolt against the name one is given, most often by our parents? What does this say about our relationship with our parents? What does it say about our desire to fit in? Or is the desire for a new name a way to stand out and be different? Don’t we all know kids who have insisted on changing their name? How long do the new names stick? How do we parents feel when our kids do this? What makes a person want to change their name? These questions intrigue me.<br /><br />I like the author’s prose style. The language is simple, but it captures well the atmosphere of a time and a place. There was one line which lyrically described a large leaf blown by the wind into the oncoming beam of a car. It spoke to me. Beautiful lines such as this make a difference to me; they enhance the reading experience. It is for this reason alone I will be reading more by the author. It is her prose style that I believe got her the 2000 Pulitzer Prize in fiction for her short story collection <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/5439.Interpreter_of_Maladies" title="Interpreter of Maladies by Jhumpa Lahiri" rel="nofollow noopener">Interpreter of Maladies</a>.<br /><br />I like and dislike different aspects of this novel. This is reflected in my rating.<br /><br />Sarita Choudbury narrates the audiobook. Her intonation of Indians speaking English is lovely to listen to. Off and on she reads too fast. Her narration I like and so have given it three stars.<br /><br />*****************<br /><br />*<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/33917.The_Namesake" title="The Namesake by Jhumpa Lahiri" rel="nofollow noopener">The Namesake</a> 3 stars<br />*<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/5439.Interpreter_of_Maladies" title="Interpreter of Maladies by Jhumpa Lahiri" rel="nofollow noopener">Interpreter of Maladies</a> 2 stars<br />*<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/17262100.The_Lowland" title="The Lowland by Jhumpa Lahiri" rel="nofollow noopener">The Lowland</a> TBR</span>
